Review what you just did. Only check for hard errors — not style or completeness.

If NO files were changed (no edit_file or write_file was used), skip verification and return:
{"success": true}

If files WERE changed:
1. If the prompt names a verify-class target (`runner:target` such as `just:verify` / `npm:ci` / `make:check`), run THAT via `run_task`. Its body is the project's full contract for "verified" — running its individual sub-commands directly via `run_command` (`go test ./...`, `npm test`, etc.) may skip steps the recipe chains (tidy, build, lint). When no verify-class target is named, fall back to whatever test/check task is available via `run_task`.
2. Any run_task that exits non-zero (output contains "❌ TASK FAILED" or "exit status") is a verification FAILURE — set success:false and include the failed task name and exit status in issues. This applies even if the cause looks unrelated to your change (e.g. a missing system tool); the user is told and decides whether the dependency is the agent's problem to solve. Do NOT rationalize a non-zero exit as "success with a known issue".
3. If the failure looks like a missing tool ("command not found", "not installed", "No such file or directory"), check whether the project ships a devcontainer: list_files at `.devcontainer`. If it exists, read `.devcontainer/devcontainer.json` (and any Dockerfile it references). If `run_command` is available, the executor can TEST the install in the live container (e.g. `apt-get install -y <tool> && <tool> --version` then re-run the failing task) before committing to a Dockerfile patch — flag this as a fix_step, e.g. `"test-install <tool> via run_command, then add it to .devcontainer/Dockerfile"`. Only fall back to `"rebuild the devcontainer with <tool> installed"` if the test install would be impossible (no `run_command`, or runtime is not a container). Never advise the human to install system tools manually when the agent can verify the install itself.
4. Use read_file to verify your edits are syntactically correct.

## Sustainability check (runs even when everything passed)

Exit codes decide success/failure — your `success` field is advisory and gets overridden from the tool stream. What the LLM verdict IS authoritative on is whether the fix will SURVIVE a fresh clone / container rebuild. Even on a clean run, scan the executor's tool history and populate `sustainability_concerns` for anything that worked in this session but won't persist:

- Package installs via `run_command` (`apt-get install`, `pacman -S`, `yay -S`, `apk add`, `dnf install`, `pip install`, `npm install -g`, `cargo install`, …) without a matching edit to `.devcontainer/Dockerfile` (or equivalent project bootstrap file). The install lives only for this container's lifetime.
- Environment variables exported in a shell (`export FOO=bar`) without being added to `.devcontainer/devcontainer.json` `containerEnv`, a `.env` checked into the repo, or the project's documented setup.
- Files written to ephemeral locations (`/tmp`, `/root`, container HOME) when the fix needs them on every run.
- One-off config tweaks applied via `run_command` (`git config`, `npm config set`, …) that aren't reflected in repo-tracked files.

When listing a concern, name the specific install/command AND where it should be persisted, e.g. `"apt-get install ripgrep was run via run_command — add it to .devcontainer/Dockerfile so it survives rebuild"`. A non-empty `sustainability_concerns` will downgrade the verdict to failure with the concerns as fix_steps, triggering a re-plan that persists them.

Leave `sustainability_concerns` empty when no devops-side fixes were applied, when the relevant Dockerfile/setup files were already edited to match, or when the change is purely workspace files (source edits, docs).

Do NOT flag style issues, incomplete explanations, or missing context.
Do NOT repeat web searches or tool calls already performed.
Only flag issues that cause builds to break, tests to fail, or incorrect file content.

Reply with ONLY a JSON object, no other text:
{
  "success": true/false,
  "issues": ["issue1", ...],
  "fix_steps": ["step1", ...],
  "sustainability_concerns": ["concern1", ...]
}

If success is true, leave issues and fix_steps empty.
If success is false:
- "issues": what is broken (build errors, test failures, wrong edits)
- "fix_steps": concrete steps to fix it

`sustainability_concerns` is independent of success — populate it whenever a non-persistent fix was applied, even on a clean run.
